    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What is a healthy BMI for my age?</summary>
        <p>For adults 20 and older, a healthy BMI is generally 18.5 to 24.9 regardless of age. However, some health organizations suggest that older adults (65+) may benefit from a slightly higher BMI range of 23 to 30, as moderate overweight in seniors is associated with lower mortality risk. For children and teens (ages 2-19), BMI is assessed using age- and sex-specific percentile charts. A BMI between the 5th and 85th percentile is considered healthy for children.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Is BMI different for men and women?</summary>
        <p>The BMI formula and category thresholds (underweight, normal, overweight, obese) are the same for men and women. However, BMI does not account for differences in body composition between sexes. Women naturally carry a higher percentage of body fat than men at the same BMI. A woman with a BMI of 24 typically has a different body fat percentage than a man with the same BMI. This is one reason many health professionals recommend using BMI alongside other metrics like waist circumference or body fat percentage for a more complete picture.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can you be healthy with a high BMI?</summary>
        <p>Yes. BMI does not distinguish between muscle, bone, and fat mass. A muscular athlete may have a BMI in the overweight or even obese range while having low body fat and excellent cardiovascular health. Studies also show that some people classified as overweight by BMI have normal blood pressure, cholesterol, and blood sugar levels. Conversely, people with a normal BMI can have metabolically unhealthy profiles. BMI is a useful population-level screening tool, but individual health depends on many factors including fitness level, waist circumference, blood markers, diet quality, and family history.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What are the limitations of BMI as a health measure?</summary>
        <p>BMI has several well-documented limitations. It does not distinguish between fat mass and lean mass (muscle, bone, water), so it can overestimate body fat in athletes and underestimate it in sedentary individuals who have lost muscle mass. It does not account for fat distribution, and abdominal fat is far more dangerous than fat carried in the hips and thighs. It uses the same thresholds for all ethnicities despite different health risk profiles. It may underestimate health risks in older adults who have lost height. And it does not reflect fitness level, diet quality, or metabolic health markers. For a more complete assessment, consider measuring body fat percentage, waist-to-hip ratio, or waist circumference alongside BMI.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

